<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tian Jiyun Concludes South Pacific Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tian Jiyun Concludes South Pacific Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105034094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0253 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105034094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Canberra, May 11 (XINHUA) -- Tian Jiyun, vice 
chairman of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC), left 
Brisbane this morning for home after winding up his week-long 
visit to Australia. 
  Australia was the last leg of Tian's four-nation tour in the 
South Pacific, which had taken him to New Zealand, Western Samoa 
and Papua New Guinea. 
  During his week-long stay in Australia, Tian and his 
entourage visited Canberra, Melbourne, Sydney and Brisbane. 
  In Canberra, he had meetings with Governor-General Bill 
Hayden, Prime Minister Paul Keating and other senior government 
officials on increasing relations between the two countries as 
well as issues of common interest. 
  He also had extensive contacts with Aussie parliamentarians 
with a view to enhancing links between the two parliaments and 
exchanged views with local businessmen on expanding economic and 
trade cooperation. 
  Tian, who started his four-nation South Pacific trip on 
April 
18, described it as "the successful, satisfactory and fruitful 
one." 
  He said that his visit to the four nations has achieved 
goals 
of "increasing understanding, getting acquainted with friends 
and promoting cooperation." 
  Tian's South Pacific nation trip was seen as China's 
attaching to the importance of parliamentary diplomacy, which 
Tian said "can play a major role in increasing friendship and 
cooperation between China and the countries in the world." 

</TEXT>

