<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Officials Take Up Leading Posts in Yunnan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ethnic Officials Take Up Leading Posts in Yunnan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105080894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0717 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105080894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kunming, May 11 (XINHUA) -- Some 40 percent of the 
provincial and prefectural officials are from ethnic minorities 
in Yunnan, a southwestern province with a large number of 
ethnic-minority inhabitants. 
  A provincial official said that of the total number of the 
province's ethnic officials 68.5 have education up to college or 
special secondary school level. More than half of them hold the 
titles as professors or technicians. 
  Yunnan is home to 25 ethnic minorities, which make up 34 
percent of its population. Most of them used to live primitive 
lives before the People's Republic of China was founded in 1949. 
To improve life and education for these ethnic people, the 
province has earmarked over one million yuan (about 110,000 U.S. 
dollars) every year to help start special training classes for 
ethnic officials. 
  Now the number of technical personnel among the ethnic 
population has hit a record high of 127,000. Many of them are 
very active in various walks of life such as agriculture, 
engineering, education, science and technology. Some have 
become acclaimed professors and research scientists. 
  At present, ethnic-minority people hold such prominent 
positions in the Communist Party, government and legislature as 
deputy party head, provincial governor and deputy governor, head 
of the provincial people's congress and chairman or 
vice-chairman of provincial committees of the Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

