<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tianjin Opens New Shipping Route to United States </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tianjin Opens New Shipping Route to United States </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105041394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0322 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105041394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, May 11 (XINHUA) -- A new direct shipping 
route from this north China port city to the west coast of the 
United States means the end of cargo shipping via Hong Kong and 
the Middle East to North America. 
  An official at the container shipping headquarters of the 
China Ocean Shipping Company, which opened the new route, said 
that the rapid growth of Sino-U.S. trade and trade with other 
Far East nations have made the opening of the new route a 
necessity. 
  According to the official, ships will leave Tianjin every 
Saturday and go via Qingdao in Shandong Province, and Kobe and 
Yokohama in Japan to Seattle in the United States. Then they 
will sail north to Vancouver in Canada and return to Tianjin via 
Kobe. 
  Six ships capable of handling a total of 2,700 containers 
will ply the new route. That will push the China Ocean Shipping 
Company from tenth position to fifth position among 100 shipping 
companies in the Pacific region in terms of shipping capacity. 
  The first port with a specialized container dock in China, 
the Tianjin port now has eight berths for containers, with an 
annual handling capacity topping one million standard 
containers. The port has opened some 160 international shipping 
routes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

