<F P=100> Northeast Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demand Increases for Telephones in Liaoning's Shenyang </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demand Increases for Telephones in Liaoning's Shenyang </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0605014094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0109 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0605014094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenyang, May 6 (XINHUA) -- More and more people in 
Shenyang city, capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province, 
are eager to have telephones installed in their homes. 
  Every day more than 400 people come to the Bureau of 
Telecommunications to apply for installation of phones. 
  An official of the bureau noted that the number of 
applicants 
peaked at 1,900 one day. 
  Experts attributed this tendency to the increase in people's 
income in the past decade. 
  On average, the cost for a telephone line for a private home 
is about 5,000 yuan. 
  Ten years ago, people would naturally regard the person with 
a home telephone as a leader or a celebrity. But now things are 
quite different, and telephones have entered common people's 
homes. 
  From the mid-1980s on, Shenyang has invested a lot of money 
to introduce automatic telephone exchanges, program-controlled 
telex switching equipment, mobile telephone systems and radio 
tracking systems from Belgium, Sweden, and Taiwan. 
  The telecommunications network in Shenyang became 
program-controlled last year, and its capacity has been expanded 
to 420,000 lines. 
  From the beginning of the 1990s, applicants for telephone 
installations in Shenyang have multiplied year after year. 
  In 1993, those who applied for prIvate telephones aCcounted 
for 80 percent of the total applicants. 
  From 1990 to 1993, the number of telephones installed each 
year was 13,000, 20,000, 40,000 and 100,000. 
  But the rate of installation is still far lower than that of 
the increasing number of applicants for private telephones. 
  Now there is a telephone for every ten people in Shenyang, 
said the official. 
  Private telephones have become popular because of the 
convenience they bring. On the first day of the spring 
festival, more than 600 people extended greetings to relatives 
abroad by telephone from their homes. 
  This year, Shenyang will enlarge its telephone capacity by 
an 
added 377,000 lines and install 150,000 telephones for citizens. 
  The city will also construct and reconstruct 10 urban 
telephone service bureaus. 
  By 1995, the total telephone lines in the city will reach 
1.15 million or a telephone for every five people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-49826 </DOCNO>
